
BLE Module Pin	Raspberry Pi Physical Pin	GPIO Number	Description
VCC	Pin 1 or Pin 17	3.3V or 5V	Power Supply
GND	Pin 6 or Pin 9	GND	Ground
TX	Pin 10	GPIO15 (UART RX)	UART Receive
RX	Pin 8	GPIO14 (UART TX)	UART Transmit

1 Enable UART
sudo raspi-config

Go to Interface Options â†’ Enable Serial Port

Disable login shell over serial

Enable serial hardware
2. Reboot Raspberry Pi

sudo reboot
3. Install Python Serial package

pip install pyserial
4. Use this code for execution
To check the serial port:  Run in terminal:

ls -l /dev/serial*
dev/serial0 -> ttyAMA0
/dev/serial1 -> ttyS0
Make sure serial is enabled:

grep -i uart /boot/firmware/config.txt
You should see something like:

enable_uart=1


If not, add this line:

sudo nano /boot/firmware/config.txt


Add:

enable_uart=1


Save (CTRL+O, Enter) and reboot:

sudo reboot

BLE CODE:

import serial
import time

# Open serial port for HC-05
# Change /dev/serial0 to /dev/ttyAMA0 or /dev/ttyS0 if needed
uart_channel = serial.Serial("/dev/ttyAMA0", baudrate=9600, timeout=1)

print("Waiting for data from HC-05...")

try:
    while True:
        if uart_channel.in_waiting > 0:  # Check if data is available
            data = uart_channel.readline().decode('utf-8', errors='ignore').strip()
            if data:
                print("Received:", data)
        time.sleep(0.1)  # Avoid CPU overuse
except KeyboardInterrupt:
    print("Exiting...")
finally:
    uart_channel.close()

